<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Factorial !</h1>=20


<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"width:60px; text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mat=
hsisfun.com/numbers/images/factorial.svg" alt=3D"Factorial Symbol" height=
=3D"117" width=3D"26"></td>
			<td>=20
<p>The <b>factorial function</b> (symbol: <b><span class=3D"larger">!</span=
></b>) says to <b>multiply all whole numbers</b> from our chosen number dow=
n to 1.</p>=20
<p>Examples:</p>=20
<ul class=3D"large">=20
	<li><b>4!</b> <em>=3D</em> 4 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 1 <em>=3D</em> 24</l=
i>=20
	<li><b>7!</b> <em>=3D</em> 7 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 5 =C3=97 4 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 2 =
=C3=97 1 <em>=3D</em> 5040</li>=20
	<li><b>1!</b> <em>=3D</em> 1</li>=20
</ul></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div><br>


<div class=3D"words">We usually say (for example) <b> 4!</b> as "4 factoria=
l", but some people say "4 shriek" or "4 bang".</div>


<h2>Calculating From the Previous Value</h2>=20

<p>Each factorial builds on the previous one, making calculations easier:</=
p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/f=
actorial-how.svg" alt=3D"factorial multiply" height=3D"61" width=3D"279"></=
p>=20
<p>As a table:</p>=20
<div class=3D"beach">

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<th scope=3D"col">n</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">n!</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">&nbsp;</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">&nbsp;</th>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>1</td>
			<td><b>1</b></td>
			<td>1</td>
			<td>1</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>2</td>
			<td>2 =C3=97 <b>1</b></td>
			<td>=3D 2 =C3=97 <b>1!</b></td>
			<td>=3D 2</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>3</td>
			<td>3 =C3=97 <b>2 =C3=97 1</b></td>
			<td>=3D 3 =C3=97 <b>2!</b></td>
			<td>=3D 6</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>4</td>
			<td>4 =C3=97 <b>3 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 1</b></td>
			<td>=3D 4 =C3=97 <b>3!</b></td>
			<td>=3D 24</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>5</td>
			<td>5 =C3=97 <b>4 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 1</b></td>
			<td>=3D 5 =C3=97 <b>4!</b></td>
			<td>=3D 120</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>6</td>
			<td>and so on</td>
			<td>and so on</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div><br>


<ul>=20
	<li>To work out 6!, multiply 120 by <b>6</b> to get 720</li>=20
	<li>To work out 7!, multiply 720 by <b>7</b> to get 5040</li>=20
	<li>And so on</li>=20
</ul>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 9! equals 362.880. Try to calculate 10!</h3>=20

	<p>10! <em>=3D</em> 10 =C3=97 9!</p>=20
	<p>10! <em>=3D</em> 10 =C3=97 362.880 <em>=3D</em> <b>3.628.800</b></p>=20
	</div>
<p>So the rule is:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">n! <em>=3D</em> n =C3=97 (n=E2=88=921)!</p>=20
<p>Which says</p>=20
<p class=3D"center">"the factorial of any number is <b>that number</b> time=
s the <b>factorial of (that number minus 1)</b>"</p>=20
<p>So 10! <em>=3D</em> 10 =C3=97 9!, ... and 125! <em>=3D</em> 125 =C3=97 1=
24!, and so on.</p>=20


<h2>What About "0!"</h2>=20

<p>Zero Factorial is interesting ... it is generally agreed that <b>0! <em>=
=3D</em> 1</b>.</p>=20
<p>It may seem funny that multiplying no numbers together results in 1, but=
 let's follow the pattern backwards from, say, 4! like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/z=
ero-factorial.svg" alt=3D"24/4=3D6, 6/3=3D2, 2/2=3D1, 1/1=3D1" height=3D"14=
9" width=3D"130"></p>=20
<p>And in many equations using 0! <em>=3D</em> 1 just makes sense.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images=
/arrange-letters-acb.jpg" alt=3D"arrange letters acb" height=3D"113" width=
=3D"200"></p>=20

	<h3>Example: how many ways can we arrange letters (without repeating)?</h3=
>=20

	<ul>=20
		<li>For 1 letter "a" there is only <b>1</b> way: a</li>=20
		<li>For 2 letters "ab" there are <b>1=C3=972=3D2</b> ways: ab, ba</li>=20
		<li>For 3 letters "abc" there are <b>1=C3=972=C3=973=3D6</b> ways: abc ac=
b cab bac bca cba</li>=20
		<li>For 4 letters "abcd" there are <b>1=C3=972=C3=973=C3=974=3D24</b> way=
s: (try it yourself!)</li>=20
		<li>and so on</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>The formula is simply <b>n!</b></p>=20
	<p>Now ... how many ways can we arrange no letters? Just one way, an empty=
 space:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images=
/arrange-letters-none.jpg" alt=3D"arrange letters none" height=3D"113" widt=
h=3D"200"></p>=20
	<p>So <b>0! <em>=3D</em> 1</b></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Where is Factorial Used?</h2>=20

<p>One area they are used is in <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/combi=
natorics/combinations-permutations.html">Combinations and Permutations</a>.=
 We had an example above, and here is a slightly different example:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images=
/winners.jpg" alt=3D"1st, 2nd and 3rd" height=3D"202" width=3D"219"></p>=20

	<h3>Example: How many different ways can 7 people come 1<sup>st</sup>, 2<s=
up>nd</sup> and 3<sup>rd</sup>?</h3>=20

	<p>The list is quite long, if the 7 people are called <i>a,b,c,d,e,f</i> a=
nd <i>g</i> then the list includes:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><i>abc, abd, abe, abf, abg, acb, acd, ace, acf, ...</i=
> and so on.</p>=20
	<p>The formula is <span class=3D"intbl"><em>7!</em><strong>(7=E2=88=923)!<=
/strong></span><b> <em>=3D</em> <span class=3D"intbl"><em>7!</em><strong>4!=
</strong></span></b></p>=20
	<p>Let us write the multiplies out in full:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em style=3D"text-align:r=
ight;"><b>7 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 5 =C3=97 4 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 1</b></em><=
strong style=3D"text-align:right;"><b>4 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 1</b></str=
ong></span><b> <em>=3D</em> 7 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 5</b></p>=20
	<p>That was neat. The <b>4 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 1</b> "cancelled out",=
 leaving only <b>7 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 5</b>. And:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><b>7 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 5 <em>=3D</em> 210</b></p>=
=20
	<p>So there are 210 different ways that 7 people could come 1<sup>st</sup>=
, 2<sup>nd</sup> and 3<sup>rd</sup>.</p>=20
	<p>Done!</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is 100! / 98!</h3>=20

	<p>Using our knowledge from the previous example we can jump straight to t=
his:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>100!</em><strong>98!<=
/strong></span> <em>=3D</em> 100 =C3=97 99 <em>=3D</em> 9900</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Factorials also appear in probability and statistics, such as calculatin=
g <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/lottery.html">lottery odds</a>=
.</p>=20


<h2>A Small List</h2>=20

<div class=3D"beach">

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<th scope=3D"col">n</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">n!</th>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>0</td>
			<td>1</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>1</td>
			<td>1</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>2</td>
			<td>2</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>3</td>
			<td>6</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>4</td>
			<td>24</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>5</td>
			<td>120</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>6</td>
			<td>720</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>7</td>
			<td>5.040</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>8</td>
			<td>40.320</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>9</td>
			<td>362.880</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>10</td>
			<td>3.628.800</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>11</td>
			<td>39.916.800</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>12</td>
			<td>479.001.600</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td>13</td>
