<h2>Interesting Facts</h2>=20

<div class=3D"fun">=20
<p><b>Six weeks</b> is exactly <b>10!</b> seconds (=3D3.628.800)</p>=20
<p>Here is why:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;"><i>Seconds in 6 weeks:</i></td>
			<td style=3D"width:20px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">60 =C3=97 60 =C3=97 24 =C3=97 7 =C3=97 =
6</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;"><i>Factor some numbers:</i></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(2 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 10) =C3=97 (3 =C3=97=
 4 =C3=97 5) =C3=97 (8 =C3=97 3) =C3=97 7 =C3=97 6</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;"><i>Rearrange:</i></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">2 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 4 =C3=97 5 =C3=97 6 =
=C3=97 7 =C3=97 8 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 10</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;"><i>Last 3=C3=973=3D9:</i></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">2 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 4 =C3=97 5 =C3=97 6 =
=C3=97 7 =C3=97 8 =C3=97 9 =C3=97 10</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"fun">=20
<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/=
deck-cards.jpg" alt=3D"deck of cards" height=3D"148" width=3D"200"></p>=20
<p>There are <b>52!</b> ways to shuffle a deck of cards.</p>=20
<p>That is <b>8,0658175... =C3=97 10<sup>67</sup></b></p>=20
<p>Just shuffle a deck of cards and it is likely that you are the <b>first =
person ever</b> with that particular order.</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"fun">=20
<p>There are about <b>60!</b> atoms in the observable Universe.</p>=20
<p>60! is about <b> 8,320987... =C3=97 10<sup>81</sup></b> and the current =
estimates are between 10<sup>78</sup> to 10<sup>82</sup> atoms in the obser=
vable Universe.</p>=20
</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"fun">=20
<p><b>70!</b> is approximately <b>1,197857... x 10<sup>100</sup></b>, which=
 is just larger than a Googol (the digit 1 followed by one hundred zeros).<=
/p>=20
<p><b>100!</b> is approximately 9,3326215443944152681699238856 x 10<sup>157=
</sup></p>=20
<p><b>200!</b> is approximately 7,8865786736479050355236321393 x 10<sup>374=
</sup></p>=20
</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>


<h1>Advanced Topics</h1>=20


<h3>A Close Formula!</h3>=20


<div class=3D"center larger">n! =E2=89=88 (<span class=3D"intbl"><em>n</em>=
<strong>e</strong></span>)<sup>n</sup> <span style=3D"font-size:120%;">=E2=
=88=9A</span><span class=3D"overline">2<span class=3D"times">=CF=80</span>n=
 </span></div><!-- n! APR ( n/e )^n SQR( 2PIn ) -->=20
<p>The "=E2=89=88" means "approximately equal to". Let us see how good it i=
s:</p>=20
<div class=3D"beach">

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<th scope=3D"col">n</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">n!</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">Close Formula<br>
(to 2 Decimals)</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">Accuracy<br>
(to 4 Decimals)</th>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>1</td>
			<td>1</td>
			<td>0,92</td>
			<td>0,9221</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>2</td>
			<td>2</td>
			<td>1,92</td>
			<td>0,9595</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>3</td>
			<td>6</td>
			<td>5,84</td>
			<td>0,9727</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>4</td>
			<td>24</td>
			<td>23,51</td>
			<td>0,9794</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>5</td>
			<td>120</td>
			<td>118,02</td>
			<td>0,9835</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>6</td>
			<td>720</td>
			<td>710,08</td>
			<td>0,9862</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>7</td>
			<td>5040</td>
			<td>4980,40</td>
			<td>0,9882</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>8</td>
			<td>40320</td>
			<td>39902,40</td>
			<td>0,9896</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>9</td>
			<td>362880</td>
			<td>359536,87</td>
			<td>0,9908</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>10</td>
			<td>3628800</td>
			<td>3598695,62</td>
			<td>0,9917</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>11</td>
			<td>39916800</td>
			<td>39615625,05</td>
			<td>0,9925</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>12</td>
			<td>479001600</td>
			<td>475687486,47</td>
			<td>0,9931</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p>If you don't need perfect accuracy this may be useful.</p>=20
<p>Note: it is called "Stirling's approximation" and is based on a simplife=
d version of the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/gamma-functi=
on.html">Gamma Function</a>.</p>=20
<p><br></p>=20

<h3>What About Negatives?</h3>=20

<p>Can we have factorials for negative numbers?</p>=20
<p><b>Yes ... but not for n</b><b>egative <i>integers.</i></b></p>=20
<p>Negative <i>integer</i> factorials, like (=E2=88=921)!, (=E2=88=922)!, a=
nd so on, are <b>undefined</b>.</p>=20
<p>Let's start with 3! <em>=3D</em> 3 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 1 <em>=3D</em> 6 and =
go <b>down</b>:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"width:20px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">2!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:20px;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">3! / 3</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:20px;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">6 / 3</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:20px;">=3D</td>
			<td>2</td>
			<td style=3D"width:30px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">1!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">2! / 2</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">2 / 2</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td>1</td>
			<td><br>
</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">0!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">1! / 1</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">1 / 1</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td>1</td>
			<td><br>
</td>
			<td><i>&nbsp; which is why 0!=3D1</i></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;"> (=E2=88=921)!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">0! / 0</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td>1 / 0</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td>?</td>
			<td><br>
</td>
			<td><i><b>&nbsp; oops, dividing by zero is undefined</b></i></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>And from there on down <b>all integer factorials are undefined</b>.</p>=
=20
<p><br></p>=20

<h3>What About Decimals?</h3>=20

<p>Can we have factorials for numbers like 0,5 or =E2=88=923,217?</p>=20
<p><b>Yes we can!</b> But we need to use the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsis=
fun.com/numbers/gamma-function.html">Gamma Function</a> (advanced topic).</=
p>=20
<p>Factorials can also be negative (except for negative integers).</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<h3>Half Factorial</h3>=20

<p>But I can tell you the factorial of <b>half</b> (=C2=BD) is <b>half of t=
he square root of <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/pi.html">pi=
</a></b> .</p>=20
<p>Here are some "half-integer" factorials:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;">(=E2=88=92=C2=BD)!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:30px;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:100px;"><span class=3D"times">=E2=
=88=9A=CF=80</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(=C2=BD)!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(=C2=BD)<span class=3D"times">=E2=88=9A=
=CF=80</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(3/2)!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(3/4)<span class=3D"times">=E2=88=9A=CF=
=80</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(5/2)!</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=3D</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">(15/8)<span class=3D"times">=E2=88=9A=
=CF=80</span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p>It still follows the rule that "the factorial of any number is <b>that n=
umber times the factorial of (1 smaller than that number)</b>", because</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center">(3/2)! <em>=3D</em> (3/2) =C3=97 (1/2)!<br>
(5/2)! <em>=3D</em> (5/2) =C3=97 (3/2)!</p>=20
<p>Can you figure out what (7/2)! is?</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<h3>Double Factorial!!</h3>=20

<p>A double factorial is like a normal factorial but we skip every second n=
umber:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>8!! <em>=3D</em> 8 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 4 =C3=97 2 <em>=3D</em> 384</li>=20
	<li>9!! <em>=3D</em> 9 =C3=97 7 =C3=97 5 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 1 <em>=3D</em> 94=
5</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Notice how we multiply all even, or all odd, numbers.</p>=20
<p>Note: if we want to apply factorial twice we write (n!)!</p>=20
